{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_jemhadar_ver01/data/sn85042243/00383346162/1937120801/0884.xml":{"full_text":"\u2022RAILS AND STEELS\nSHOW LEADERS WAY\nTO 2-POINT GAINS\nfi&Ily Come* After Mixed Open\ning, Freight Rate Boost\nThought Likely\nNew York, Dec. 8.\u2014(IP)\u2014Buyingsup\nport for rails and steels aided other\ngroups in the stock market Wednes\nday and leading shares pushed up\nfractions to 2 points or more.\n4\nThe rally came belatedly after a\nmixed opening, but gained force as the\nafternoon wore on. Fairly large'blocks\nv.ere snapped up as buyers sought\n\"oversold\" issues.\nTraders appeared heartened by con\ncrete proposals for business revival\nset forth by industrial executives at\nIf the annual convention of the Na\ntional Association of Manufacturers\nWall Street had apparently made up\nIts mind chances for freight rate in\ncreases had improved.\nFarm implement shares were stim\nulated by reports agriculturists were\nstocking up against next year's needs.\nChain store sales in the middlewest\nreflected increased buying power in\nthe rural sections.\nBonds were higher. Commodities,\ntfter a mixed start, pointed higher\nForeign markets were irregular.\nLivestock\nSO. ST. PUAL\nSouth St. Paul, Dec. 8. -W\u2014 \u00abJ. S\nDep. Agr.)\u2014Cattle, 3,000, slaughter\nsteers opening steady, good fed steers\nup to 9.00 some held higher good\nheifers 7.00-8.00 plafti to medium\ncows 4.25-5.50 bulls strong, bulk 5.25\n6.25 stockers slow.\nCalves, 2,500 vealers steady, most\ngood to choice 7.00-8.00 strictly\nchoice up to 9.50.\nHogs, 13,000,850 direct active to all\ninterests, steady to a dime lower top\n8.00 for 170 pounds down good choice\n140-220 lbs., 7.70-8.00 220-270 lbs..\n7.40-80 270-350 lbs., 7.10-40 good\nsows 6.80-90 good stags 6.5-7.00 pigs\nvery scarce, average cost Tuesday\n7.61 weight 235 lbs.\nSheep 4,000 no heavy sales slaugh\nter lambs, buyers talking lower sell\ners asking fully steady part deck 117\nlb. feed yearlings 7.50 indications\nsteady on slaughter ewes and feeding\nlambs good to choice lambs Tuesday\n#8.50 to 8.90 big bulk 8.75 good to\nchoice range feeding lambs Tuesday\n8.00 to 8.70.\nDairy cows, trading light due to cold\nweather quotations little changed,\ngood springer cows considered salable\naround $70 to $80.\nCHICAGO\nChicago. Dec. 8.\u2014 (U. S. D. A.)\n\u2014Hogs 22.000, Including: 5000 direct\nearly market steady to 10 lower than\nTuesday's average now mostly 10-15\noff top 8.50 most early sales g-ood\nand choice 150-200 lb., 8.35-50 some\nsales now 8.25-40 bulk good and\nchoice 210-250 lb., 8.00-35 most good\npacking sows T.OO-4-O practical top\n7.40.\nCattle 11,004, calves 1500 fed steers\nand yearlings steady to 25 lower\nsho stock in very liberal supply, un\nevenly steady to 25 off mostly 25\ndown on heifers and light young cows\nbulls weak at 6.75 down, mostly* $.50\ndown vealers scarce and steady at\n10.50 down very little done on steers\nfew early sales 8.00-10.50 with sprink\nling at 11.00 upward best choice light\nsteers selling at 13.50 upward of 1:0\nloads light young cows and fed heif\ners In crop best heifers early 9 60\n\u2022*vith bulk at 8.00 down.\nSheep 11,04)0 including 1500 direct\nfat lambs more active than early\nmost sales about steady at 9.00 down\n\u00abarly top 9.25 paid by local packer\nbest held higher comparatively little\ndone on yearlings sheep about steady\nnative ewes around 3.50-4.50 feeding\nlambs little changed good range feed\ners 8.60.\nSIOUX CITY\nSioux City, Dec. 8.\u2014(fl*)\u2014(U.S. D. A.)\n\u2014Cattle 3000 calves 300 slaughter\nsteers and yearlings moderately ac\nlive, fully steady fed heifers firm\ncows fairly active, unchanged stock\ners and feeders scarce, steady numer\nous lots fed steers and yearlings 7.50\n8.50 carlots held above 9.25 strictly\nchoice quoted around 13.00 load lots\nMO'O lb. heifers up to 7.50 few good\nkoshers 8.75 bulk beef cows 4/60-3.50\nfew around 5.75 cutter grades mainly\n3.50*4.00 small lots good light stock\nsteers up to 6.85.\nHogs 2500, Including 250 direct\nslow, mostly 10 higher to shippers and\ntraders good and choice 160-230 lb.\nbutchers 7.75-85 top 7.90 to traders:\npackers bidding 7.75 on weights 240\nlbs. down light lights and pigs to\nfeeders weak to 25 lower at 7.75-8.00\npacking sows 7.00-10 stags mostly\n7.00\nSheep 200-0 early fat Iamb bids\naround 25 lower indications ewes\neasier salable largely 4.25 down\n4 feeder lambs scarce.\nCHICAGO POTATOES\nChicago. Dec. 8 m\u2014 (U. S. D. AO\nPotatoes, 101, on track 295. total US.\nshipments 629 about steady, supplies\nrather liberal, demand slow sacked\nper cwt. Idaho Russet Burbanks US.\nXo. 1, 1.37*4-45: US. So. 2. 1.10-30\nColorado Red McClures US. No. 1,\n1.40-50 North Dakota Bliss triumphs\n80 per cent US, No. 1, 1.05 Early Ohios\n85 per cent US. No. 1, 1.10 Minnesota\ncobblers 80-85 per cent US. No. 1,\n1.05-10 Wisconsin round whites US.\nNo 1, 1.0*5: Michigan Green Mountains\nVS. commercials, 2 inch minimum 1.30\nRusset rurals US. commercials 1.05.\nMINNEAPOLIS FLOUR\nMinneapolis. Dec. 8.\u2014(^\u2014Flour,\ncarload lots, per barrel in 98 pound\ncotton sacks: Family patents un\nchanged 6.25-45 standard patents, 15\nlower 5-45-65.\nShipments 20,263.\nPure bran 18.50*19.00.\nStandard middlings 18.50-19.W.\nBOSTON WOOL\nBoston, Dec. 8.\u2014(\u00a3\u2022)\u2014(U. S. D. A.)\u2014\nVery little business was being trans\nacted in greasy combing domestic\nwools Wednesday. Small quantities\nof good French combing length fine\nterritorial wool In the original bags\n-were selling around 70 scoured basis.\nCountry-packed and quarter blood\nfleeces in mixed grade lots were re\nported to have brought 30 to 31 in the\ngrease. Graded combing Ohio fleeces\nwere available in some houses at 30\nto 31 in the grease for quarter blood\nand at SI to 32 for blood.\nCHICAGO CASH GRAIN\nChicago, Dec. 8.\u2014(\u00a30\u2014Cash wheat:\nNo. 2 hard 1.00 sample grade hard\n82H No. 3 mixed 96-99.\nCorn: No. 3 mixed 54 No. 3 yel\nlow 54%-55% No. 2 white 56%-%.\nOats No. 1 white 33U-H sample\n32%.\nSoy beans: No. 2 yellow 92%-93%.\nBarley: Feed 42-60 malting 75-64.\nTimothy 2.60-95.\nClover 28.04-33.00 sweet clover\nS.25*9.00.\nDULUTH CASH GRAIN\nDuluth, Dec. 8.\u2014VP)\u2014Closing cash\nprices. Wheat: No. 1 heavy dark\nnorthern spring l.im-1.21H No. 1\ndark northern l.MH-1.19% No. 2,\n1.08H-1.16H No. 3, 1.04^-1.14% No.\n4. 1.00%-1.09% No. 5. 94^-1.04% No.\n1 northern 1.08%-1.11H. No. 1 dark\nliard winter Montana 1.03%. Durum:\nNo. 1 hard amber 92%-1.10% No. 2,\n90tt-1.04tt No. 3. 8flfe-1.06ft No, 4,\n86%-1.02H: No. 5, 84%-98%. No. 1 fed\ndurum 86%.\nFlax No. 1, (plus dock) 1.97-2.07.\nRye No. 2, 69\u00ab4-\u00abi.\nOats No. a white 34%,\nBarley: Malting HMO feed U%\n82%.\nGrain Quotations\nBISMARCK GRAIN\n(Finished by Rnnell-Nlllcr Co.)\nDec. 8\nNo. 1 dark northern, 58 Hm\nNo. 2 dark northern, 57 lbs S3\nNo. 3 dark northern, 56 lbs .91\nNo. 3 dark northern, 59 lbs\nNo. 4 dark northern, 54 lte .85\nNo. 4 dark northern, 53 lbs .83\nNo. 5 dark northern, 52 lbs 81\nNo. 5 dark northern, 51 lbs .79\nNo. 5 dark northern, 50 lb6 .77\nSample Grain:\n49 lbs., 75 48 lbs., 73 47 lbs., 71\n46 lbs., 69 45 lbs., 67 44 lbs., 65\n43 lbs., 63 42 lbs., 61 41 lbs., 59\n40 lbs., 57 39 lbs., 55 38 lbs., 53\n37 lbs.. 51.\nNo. 1 hard amber durum .71\nNo. 1 mixed durum .66\nNo. 1 red durum 71\nNo. 1 flax 1.73\nNo. 2 flax 1.70\nNo. 1 rye\nBarley .38\nOats 19\nHard winter wheat 80\nCHICMiO RANGE\nChicago. Dec. 8.\u2014(#)\u2014\nWheat-- Open Hlch Low\nDec 33% .97% 94%\nMav .92% .94% .92%\nJuly .86% .88% .86%\nCorn-\nLard\u2014\nCln\u00abe\n.97%\n.94%\n.88%\nDec. .54H .54% .53%\nMav 57'* 58 \"a .57%\nJuly .58% .59 .58%\nOats\u2014\n.54%\n.57%\n.58%\nDec .31% .31% .31%\nMay 20% .30% .30%\nJuly 29% .29% .29%\nSov Beans\nDec\nMay .94\nJuly 55%\nRve\u2014\n31%\n30%\n.29%\n.92%\n.94\n.95%\nDec 69 .69% .68%\nMay 69% .70% 69%\nJuly 65% .66% .64%\n68%\n.70%\n66%\nDec 8.55 8.65 8.55\nJan 8.65 8 75 8.?2\nMay 8.95 9.07