51 .52% 50%\n4 vellow.... .48% 50%\n5 vellow.... .45% 48\n2 mixed.... .50% .51 .50%\n3 mixed.... .48% .50 .48%\n4 mixed.... .46 .48 4\u00ab\n5 mixed.... .43 .45%\n.45%\nOats\u2014\n2 white.... .29% .29% 28%\n3 white.... .28% .28% 28%\n4 white.... 26% .28%\nBarley\u2014\nCh to fey.. 79\n9.0\nMed to Kd.. .49 .72\nLower ards .47 SZ\nFeed .38 .55\nRve\u2014\nNo. 2 .68% .72%\nFlax\nNo. 1-98 2.09\nRANGES OF CARLOT SALES\nMinneapolis, Dec. 8.\u2014(if)\u2014Kanft of\ncarlot grain .sales\nWheat: No. 1 heavy dark northern\nspring 1 17 No. 3 dark northern 1.11%\n12% sample grade dark northern\n90H-92H No. 1 hard* amber durum\n03te-1.07%.\nCorn: No 2 yellow 52-3SU.\nOats: No. 2 white f&tt No. I heavy\nwhite 31%.\nHye: No. 2, 70Vi-73.\nBarley: No. 3 malting 76H-79 No. 1.\n2-78.\nFlax: Not quoted.\nMINNEAPOLIS POT\nATOMS\nMinneapolis, Dec. 8.~-4P)'-\u00ab-AtoDt&na\nRusset Burbanks, JfS. No. 1,1.10. Oth\ners unchanged.\nw\nCHICAGO WHEAT UP\nONE-TWO CENTS ON\nSPITED RALLIES\nGermany, France May Buy Low\n\u2022r Grades of American Grain\nCorn Cent Up\nChicago, Dec. 8.\u2014ff\u2014Late brisk\nadvances switched the course of wheat\nprices Wednesday, and substituted ma\nterial gains for earlier losses.\nSuggestions that Germany and\nFrance might enter the market for\nUnited States lower grade wheats ow\ning to partial failure of the Argentine\ncrop acted as a decided stimulus for\nlate upturns of the Chicago market.\nDecember wheat contracts here de\nveloped the greatest relative stretch,\nand rose to more than 3 cents premium\nover May, the biggest premium so far\nthis season.\nAt the close, Chicago wheat futures\nwere 1 to 2 cents above yesterday's\nfinish, Dec. 97%-%, May 94%-%, corn\nunchanged to higher, Dec. 54%-%,\nMay 57%-%, and oats unchanged to\nup.\nBULLISH NEWS\nDRIVES WHEAT VP\nMinneapolis. Dec. 8.\u2014(ff)\u2014A flood\nof bullish news during the last half\nof Wednesday's session sent wheat\nfutures into higher territory today.\nReports that the Canadian wheat\nboard had cleaned up Its export hold-*\nings and\" that Germany and France\nwere due back In the International\nmarket shortly encouraged buying.\nDecember wheat closed lMc higher\nat 1.02H, May l\u00bb,ic up at l.Olft and\nJuly l^c higher at 99%.\nCrusher buying of flax futures was\na bit nure aggressive. December flax\nclosed *4c higher at 1.95, May He up\nat 1.98 and July He up at 1.99^.\nDecember and May oats each closed\nunchanged at 21% and 27%. respec\ntively. December rye closed %c high\ner at 65%, and May l^c up at 66^4.\nDecember feed barley closed %e high\ner at 45% and May ly&c higher at\n44\nCash wheat offers were light.\nSpring wheat was in good demand.\nDurum and winter ruled firm to\nstrong.\nCash corn was in good demand. Oats\ndemand was slightly better. Hye de\nmand was good. Barley was strong.\nFlax was In good demand.\nProduce Markets\nCHICAGO\nChicago, Dec. 8.\u2014(JP)\u2014Egg prices\ntended upward again Wednesday but\nbutter and poultry showed little\nchange.\nButter 7554, steady, prices un\nchanged.\nEggs 2022, firmer fresh graded, ex\ntra local 24 firsts local 23 current\nreceipts 22 refrigerator, extras\nstandards 18% firsts 18%.\nPoultry, live, 34 trucks, steady\nsprings, 4 lbs. up. Colored 19%. Ply\nmouth Rock 21, White Rock 22 Leg\nhorn chickens 16 young ducks, 4%\nlbs. up, colored 17, white 18, small\ncolored 14%, white 15% geese 7%\nother prices unchanged.\nDressed market, steady, prices un\nchanged.\nNEW YORK\nNew York, Dec. 8.\u2014(JP)\u2014Butter, 11,\n867, firmer creamery: Higher than\nextra 40-74-41% extra (92 score) 40%\nfirsts (88-91) 34%-39% seconds 84\n87) 32-33%.\nCheese, 143,302, slow prices un\nchanged.\nEggs, 22,738 firm. Mixed colors\nSpecial packs 27%-29 standards 27\nfirsts 24-24% medium and dirtleB No.\n1, 19-20, average checks 17%-18. lie\nfrigerator, spclal packs 20-23% stan\ndards 19%-% firsts 18%-19 sconds\nIS mediums, small and dirties 17 K\n17%.\nWhite: Resale of premium marks\n32%-34 nearby and mldwestern pre\nmium marks 30%-32 exchange spe\ncials 30 Midwestern, exchange stan\ndards 28-29, nearby, fancy mediums\n23%-26 nearby and western, exchange\nmediums and top pullets 21%-23\naverage pullets 21 Pacific coast, jum\nbo and premiums 32-47 specials 30%\n31 standards 30Vi-%: nearby and\nwestern, special packs 29 nearby,\nsmall to mediums 23.\nDuck eggs: Fancy to extra fancy\n*7-30.\nDressed poultry steady boxes,\nfresh: chickens, fair to fancy, fryers\n20%-2*6% roasters 21-27%. Turkeys,\nMaryland 26-29. Other fresh and froz\nen prices unchanged.\nLive poultry, by freight, firmer\nchickens. Rocks 22-24, mostly 23 col\nored 20 Leghorn 17, broilers un\nquoted. Fowls, colored 23-25 Leg\nhorn 17-18, mostly 18. Old roosters\n16-17, mostly 17.v Turkeys, hen 25\ntoms 21-22, mostly 21. Ducks 20-21,\nmostly 21.\nBy express, steady chickens, Rocks\n19-28, mostly 23 crosses 21 colored\n16-22. mostly 16-20 Leghorn 14%-23,\nmostly 14%-18. Broilers, Rocks 25\n29%, mostly 27-29 crosses 18-29, most\nly 22-27% reds 23 colored 22 Leg\nhorn 22-23, mostly 22. Fowls, colored\n18-25, mostly 24-25 Leghorn 14-22,\nmostly 20-22 old roosters 17. Tur\nkeys, hens 26, toms 22. Ducks 25%.\nBUTTER AND EGG FUTURES\nChicago, Dec. 8.\u2014lff)\u2014.\nButter Futures, Storage Standards:\nHigh Low* Close\nDecember 33% 33% 33%\nJanuary 33% 33V* 33%\nFebruary 33% 3-3 33%\nEgg Futures, Refrigerator Standards:\nDecember 18% 1S% 18%\nJanuary 18H IS 18\nFresh Graded Firsts:\nFebruary 20% 20% 20%\nMiscellaneous\nMONEY RATES\nNew York, Dec. 8.\u2014(JP)\u2014Call money\nsteady, 1 per cent all day.\nPrime commercial paper 1 per cent.\nTime loans steady. 60-90 days 1%\n-6 mos. 1% per cent,\nBankers acceptances unchanged.\nFOREIGN EXCHANGE\nSew York, Dec. 8.\u2014(A*)\u2014Foreign\nexchange steady Great Britain de\nmand in dollars, others in cents. Great\nBritain 4.99% France 4.99% Italy\n6 26% Germany free 40.32 reg. 21.45\ntravel 25.85 Norway 25.10 Sweden\n.75 Montreal In New York 100.01\n*16.\nMINNEAPOLIS STOCKS\nMinneapoli