 fair play\nmake it advisable Letters must\nbe limited to 600 words.\nTHE IN-BETWEEN COUNTY\nWilton. N. Dak.,\nNov. 22, 1937\nEditor, Tribune:\nThe article on irrigation and\nmethods of successful farming in our\npart of North Dakota are always in\nteresting. I believe after studying our\nproblem that, In a more or less de\nfined way, the state should be divided\ninto three districts: the eastern part\nwhere there Is plenty of rainfall for\nsuccessful farming, the western part\nwhere lt probably should be con\nsidered principally a range country\nand the central part which seems to\nme might be called an In-Between\nCountry.\nI looked in the geography to see\nv. here the glaciers had been to see if\nthat had any bearing on our agricul\nture and believe that may be In\ncluded In some measure in our retain\ning.\nThe Missouri and Ohio rivers bound\na great part of the southern terminus\nthe glacial area. In soil topography\nand water supply, lakes that are\ndwindling and underground water\nwhich is likely also receedlng, we may\nind some factors in a general ap\nproach to our problem.\nAs an instance in the disappearance\nlakes an acquaintance tells that\nmany years ago they caught a wagon\nload of fish in two hours in Crooke\nlake, now dry, near Turtle lake. It\nhsrly seems possible that in 40 or\n50 years we would notice changes at\ntributable to lessening of glacial ef\nfrct but lake levels are lowering.\nThe building of many dams which\nLi now being carried out\u2014and per\nhaps Missouri river diversion\u2014mav\nccunteract this trend. A little more\nra(nfali would mean much.\nGet the land back to grass does\nnot seem altogether the logical solv\ning of our problem, and we couldnt\ngel it back to grass for a good long\ntime if we wanted to. If we did have\nit all to grass we would have a harl\ntime to get feed enough for\nwouldn't have straw, corn, millet, etc.\nn help out.\nSo, it looks like we should raw!\nmore stock, do more dairying, raising\ngreat deal of feed on our cultivated\nlands and find methods of success\nproceedure to raise some acreag*\nof paying cash crops.\nGrain fanning is\nquit*\nexpensive\nMale Help-Wanted\nSCIENCE reconditions motors while\nyou drive. Call or write at once\nfor territory. Room 712, Patterson\nHotel.\n33\n9tt\n21M\n63\n7*\n37*\n6H\n11\n18H\n18H\n15\n23%\n8K\n64%\n4%\n20K\n8tt\n23%\ni3y*\n12%\n32%\n25%\n26%\n4%\n12%\n2%\n6%\n70%\n23%\n28%\n83\n40%\n21%\n46%\n36\n35%\n12\n7%\n7%\n4%\n14%\n2%\n19%\n41%\n29%\n24%\n59\n15\n23%\n15%\n21%\n23\n14\n23%\n14%\n8%\n5%\n30%\n34%\n45\n10%\nPersonal\nTYPEWRITERS sale, rent, service, all\noffice machines. Typewriter Sales\nand Service, 108 3rd, Bismarck.\nPhone 68.\nFemale Help Wanted\nADDRESS postcards Cash paid in\nadvance. Everything supplied Ue\ntails free. Hoosler Mailing Service\nBox 26. Mishawaka. Ind.\nCoal for Sale\nWILTON or Center coal, two to six\nton loads, $2.65 per ton. Phone\n602-J. Bob Morris.\nOffice Space\nOFFICE space for rent. Available\nJan. 1st. Call at Cowan's Drug\nStore, phone 102.\nWearing Apparel\nFULL LENGTH moleskin sheep-lined\novercoat, size 43, practically new\nCheap. Inquire 416 Thayer.\nFor Rent\nFour newly-built apartments\u2014\n3 rooms and bath each\nUnfurnished\n215 Mandan Street\nInquire: 114 West Broadway or\nphone 482.\nLost\nand\n5%\n17%\n42%\n29%\n8%\n43%\n11%\n4%\n6%\n73%\n88%\n23\n4\n7\n58%\n11%\n21\n31%\n6\n28 V/\nSc O\nTim Roll\nTrans-Am\nTrl-Cont Cor\nTru-Traer\nUn Car\nUn Pac\nUn Air Corp\nUn Corp\nUn Drug\nUn Fruit\nUn Oas Imp\nUS Ind A1\nUS Pipe\nUS Sc Imp\nUS Rubber\nFound\nLOST\u2014Monday morning, white bob'\ntall rat terrier. For reward, call\n1387-W, or 1988.\nLOST\u2014Small black Scottie. Answers\nname \"Laddie.\" Left ear spilt. Re\nward. Tel. 811.\nLOST\u2014Seven months old brown rat\ntall spaniel. Reward. Call Everett\nLaFVance, 478.\nand if crops are poor one goes behind\nbecause of his Industry and the more\nindustrious he is the greater is his\nloss.\nWhere irrigation can be done lt\nshould be done. It is quite a possi\nbility, awaiting development. But\n.viere is much territory that can never\nbe watered except by rain or snow an\n1\n0 seek and find methods to success'\nully cultivate these lands, along with\nstock raising, challenges our ability\nand ingenuity. I believe lt possible of\nccomplishment and to help in tnis\nis the reason for my writing.\nWe can scarcely believe that water\nran get down into our soil but in the\nfall of 1934, one of our driest years,\nin digging a trench silo where we hu.1\nfed cattle the winter before we found\nthe clay too wet to scrape out we.'l\nfour or five feet down. That gives one\nan idea to work on, how to get mots\nture down deep into our soil.\nCan we ever raise good craps\nagain? Our chances are getting le.3\nand less lt would seem, for our land\nis getting older, with less fertility, and\nmore varieties of weeds. Rust Is cre\nating different forms and insect pests\nseem to be legion. This year ther\nwere 10 different things that de\nstrayed our crop. They were drouths,\nsoi! blowing, freezing, wireworms\nwebworms (small damage) grass\nhoppers, rust, hail and weeds and\nstill for a wonder we raised some feed\nard seed.\nCan we again raise good crops? I\nbelieve lt possible. Elimination of the.se\ndestructive agencies would help. If\nthere was plenty of rain In the spring\nthe soli wouldn't blow very much.\nThere wouldn't be drouth of course\nFreezing wouldh't be so destructive.\nThe Russian thistles would get a se'.\ntack and the grain would get the\nstart of pigeon grass and weeds. In\nct pests would be fewer if moistUie\nwere plentiful and If hall, rust, etc,\nere kept away we would have mo e\ncrop than if each of these thinjs\ntook its toll. So we see that the CO'\noperation of the Lord Is a most iffi'\nportant asset. We must also do what\nwt can.\n1 have done some observing, think\ning, questioning and listening ar.d\ngotten some ideas which seem worth\nhlle which I would like to write of\nand hope that others who have had\nsuccessful methods brought to their\nnotice will tell us of them so that we\nmay work together for a way to a\nbetter financial status In such an\narea as our In-Between Country.\nHUGH REDINGTON.\nThe 148 national forests In the\nUnited States contain more than\n,000 public camp grounds.\nBack to Pumps\nNewburyport, Mass., Dsc. 8.\u2014VP)\n\u2014Newburyport's voters sent a\ncrest-fallen Mayor Andiew J.\n(Bc&sy) Glilis back to his gasoline\npumps Wednesday.\nThe usually loquacious three\nterm mayor was silent in his de\ncisive defeat by Former Ctyy Solici\ntor James F. Carens.\nDuring his administration Oillis\nrefersed wrestling bouts, became\nInvolved In weekly wrangles with\ncity officials and threatened Isst\nsummer to pasture cows on the\nhigh school lawn to cut the\nwithout cost.\n4 BARGAIN FOR YOU\nHVTT*N'\nW. Thayer. Phone 689-W.\nGROUND floor, 5 rooms, full base\nment. Gas heat. 517 W. Thayer.\nPhone 250, Obert A. Olson.\nSIX ROOM house with garage. In\nquire at 214 Fifth St., after 6 or\nSaturday and Sunday.\nJIVE room upper duplex, attachtd\ngarage. Immediate possession. O. W\nRoberts, telephone 151 or 751.\nSIX room house at 216 Ave. West.\nInquire of Carl Eliason, phons\n1316-W.\nMODERN 6-room house. Close to\nschools. Call 2414-M.\n8-ROOM house, thoroughly modern\nPhone 107.\nMattresses\nMATTRRS8ES renovated and rebuilt.\nEither regular or spring filled. 409\n8th St Phone 1136\nStamp News\nWITH release of the Virgin\nIslands stamp Dec. 15, the\nPostoflflce Department is expected\nto announce- the 1938 philatelic\nprogram.\nIndications are now that three\ncommemoratives may be issued\nfurther marking the 150th anni\nversary of the Constitution. This\nspecial series would depict the\nthree departments of the govern\nment.\nThe legislative branch would be\nrepresented through illustration of\nthe meeting of the first congress\nunder the Constitution the execu\ntive department stamp would por\ntray the ceremonies incident to\nWashington's inaugural as first\nPresident of the United States\nand the third stamp, the Judicial,\nwould depict the creation of the\nUnited States Supreme Court in\n1789.\ne e\nConvening of a special session\nof Congress revives hopes for the\npassage of the measure permit\nting the printing of black and\nwhite illustrations of United\nStates postage stamps. The Senate\npassed this bill at the last session\nbut the House failed of favorable\naction.\ne e\nPopularity of thtf \"souvenir\"\nsheets abroad is Increasing. Ger\nmany, Spain, Belgian Congo and\nRumania have issued ..miniature\nsheets recently. Some of the sheets\nmay be denied recognition in the\nAmerican catalog since this trend\nis too pronounced.\nInteresting new issues: Manchu\nkuo\u2014four values, commemorating\ncompletion of the capital city,\nHsinking Greece\u201413 values de\npicting Grecian gods, chariot\nracing and St. Paul preaching at\nAthens Russia\u2014special airmail\nblock commemorating aviation\nrecords won by Soviet flyers in\nlast year The Soviet North Pole\nset of four values will appear in\nJanuary.\ntCopriirbt lltT. MBA Secylce. Ine\nIn tht\nTOO LATE TO CLASSIFY by Baei\n.fflpww\n\"We saw your classified ad in The Bismarck Tribune so we thought\nwe'd come down for a sample lump.\"\nTHE BISMARCK TRIBUNE\nCLASSIFIED ADVERTISING RATES\n1 day 2daya Sdnya 4daya 5 daya O daya\n10 Word\u00ae\n10 WOrdS e I\nIT Words e\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\u2022\nIB Wofdi\nIt Word* ...ee.eee.ee..\n20 Words\n25 Words\n30 Words\n85 WOrdS i.iMMMtei\n40 W OrdS eee.\n45 Words\n(MINIMUM CHARGE 45c) (All Classified ads are cash with order)\n\u20220.4a\n.00 JUS .75 .83 JN)\n\u202248 M4 .78 .80 .88 .90\n\u202251 .77 .85 #4 1.02\nJV4 .72 .81 \u202290 .00 1.08\nJIT .76 .95 1.05 1.14\n60 .80 .00 1.00 1.10 1.20\n\u202275 1.00 1.1S 1.25 .1.38 1.50\nJO 1.20 1.85 1.50 1.05 l.^O\n1.06 1.40 1.58 1.70 1.08 2.10\n1JO 1.00 1.80 2.00 2.20 2.40\n1.85 1.80 2.03 2.28 2.48 2.70\nL'USSiriKD DISPLA